					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Joachim Fortius Ringelberg"/>
					<book title="Astrologia"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Certain predictions are ridiculous, but delightful. In Joachim Fortius Ringelberg's 'Astrology'.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Mens da[e]dala, ex vna pragmatica historia, Libro, discursu; instar omnium
						historiarum, librorum, discursuum. Qui se habet, non eget alijs.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>A skillful mind taken from one pragmatic history, book, or discourse; an example for all other histories, books, and discourses.
			He who has himself, is not in want of others.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Juliani vita, à Martinio concinnata, synopsis virtutum, et historiarum
						omnium. Vt etiam Juliani ipsius Ca[e]sares. gemma gemmaru[m].
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julian"/>
					<person name="Petrus Martinius"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The life of Julian, produced by Martinius, the synopsis of virtues and all histories. Just as even Julian's emperors themselves. The gem of gems.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
